[Review by harche]: Nice fix. Replacing the length heuristic with an actual per-request coverage check (reusing the same name/subrequest matching the config build loop uses) is the right call, and applying it to all three variants is good.

One coverage note. The matching paths are exercised individually by single-request tests (`with-class-device-config` for the name match, `prioritized-list-device-config` for the subrequest match), and the new case guards against widening. What nothing in the suite asserts is the opposite direction for a multi-request claim: a config that covers every top-level request should still collapse to `Requests: nil`.

I tried making the check too strict (clearing only when the claim has a single request) and the whole suite still passed, so that kind of change would slip through CI today. Suggesting a case below that covers both requests, one by subrequest and one by name. I confirmed it passes against this PR on all three implementations and fails the too-strict version while the rest of the suite stays green. Optional, but it closes the gap cheaply. | [Review by harche]: /lgtm 


